\par }\pard \ql \fi576\li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 Plenty of people have celebrated collaborative writing (e.g., Ede and Lunsford; LeFevre), so I can invoke the medieval trope of }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 occupatio}{\f37\insrsid11210736 :  I will }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 not}{
\f37\insrsid11210736  give all the reasons why collaborative writing is a good thing;  I will }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 not}{\f37\insrsid11210736 
 write about how frequently it occurs in the world and therefore how our students should learn to use it;  nor about the collaborative dimension of writing we think of
 as private;  nor about how collaborative writing helps students learn better because of all the pooling of information, ideas, and points of view;  nor about students who have hated writing because it makes them feel lonely and helpless but who come to l
ike it when they write with others;  nor will I cite the much cited Harvard research showing how students who study together get better grades (Light).
\par But I will mention in passing one interesting benefit of collaborative writing that I\rquote ve noticed but found under-celebrated.  When people write alone, they make countless simple and complex writerly decisions }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 tacitly}{
\f37\insrsid11210736 , instinctively--without articulating the reasons for them (for example, to start with this idea, or to move that point later in the paper, or to
 change a word or phrase to modify the voice or the relationship to the reader).  And that\rquote 
s as it should be:  tacit decisions are quicker and the writer is going by feel, by ear.  As Polanyi reminds us, our tacit knowledge always outstrips our conscious a
nd articulate knowledge.  But the process of writing with someone else forces us to put many these decisions into words.  If I say to my partner, \'93Let\rquote s start with this point,\'94
 I usually have to say why--especially if I am proposing a change.  And if my pa
rtner disagrees with me, he or she will naturally give reasons for the resistance.  In short the process of collaborative writing forces students to become more conscious and articulate about rhetorical decision making.
\par What I find under-represented in our professional literature about collaborative writing are the }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 problems}{\f37\insrsid11210736 
.  First, collaborative writing is difficult and often unpleasant.  When I used to force students to write essays in pairs or groups, at least half of them would say at the end that it wa
s the worst experience of the semester.  And when I gave them the choice, relatively few took it.  Collaborative writing may be jolly and social, but it takes a long time and leads to disagreements.  Is there anyone who has not vowed never again to engage
 in a piece of committee writing?  
\par Second, the writing that results from collaboration is often pretty bad.  It is likely to be bland because the parties have to agree and they can only agree on lowest-common-denominator thinking.  And there is often a dead, \'93committee\'94
 voice--no energy or presence.  The surest proof of the existence of God is the King James translation of the Bible:  only divine intervention could have permitted a committee to produce such wonderful prose.
\par Third, the collaborative process 
often silences weaker, minority, or marginal voices.  The assertive and entitled tend to carry the day.  Whenever there is a need for consensus in group work, there is great danger of silencing weaker voices (see Clarke and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1
{\factoidname City}}Ede{\*\xmlclose}; Trimbur).  
\par In order to deal with this perplexity--that collaborative writing is at once so valuable, so important, and yet so problematic--I\rquote ve come to use the }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 collage}{\f37\insrsid11210736 
 in order to introduce collaboration in writing.  The term \'93collage\'94 was originally applied to visual art, 
but most of us are familiar with written collages:  single texts that consist of multiple and somewhat disconnected fragments.  A description of the collage first appeared in the pages of this journal (as }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 Freshman English News}{
\f37\insrsid11210736 ) when Winston Weathers published \'93The Grammars of Style: New Options in Composition.\'94  I like to define the collage by sharing the simple directions I give to students for producing one:
\par }\pard \ql \fi-144\li864\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin864\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 \u144\'90Produce or gather as much of your writing on your topic as you can.  Go fast, don\rquote t worry.  Freewriting is a good method.  Take thoughts in any order.  (Option:  add fragments of writing by others.)
\par \u144\'90Go through what you have and choose the best or potentially best bits--freely cutting to create long and short sections.  
\par \u144\'90Revise what you have, mostly by cutting, not rewriting.  Cut paragraphs and sentences;  cut phrases and words.  It\rquote s amazing what is possible with just cutting.
\par \u144\'90Figure out a pleasing order for the bits:  perhaps logical, more likely intuitive and associative--maybe even random.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 For more about the collage, see my \'93Collage: Your Cheatin\rquote  Art\'94--and also the first workshop in Elbow and Belanoff.
\par }\pard \ql \fi576\li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 Just as the solo collage serves as a bridge to the writing of regular essays, the collaborative collage serves as a bridge to full collaboration.
  But like the solo collage, the collaborative collage is valuable in its own right.  It can be as nice to stand on the bridge as on the other shore.  
\par The procedure for creating a collaborative collage is so easy and simple that it will make some people nervous.  Let me lay out the directions I give to pairs or small groups working together:  
\par }\pard \ql \fi-144\li864\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin864\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 \u144\'90Individually, write as much as you can about the topic.  Write your own thoughts.  It\rquote 
s fine to use rough, exploratory writing.  Try to exploit the insights, language, and energy that come from moving fast and getting caught up in your thinking and feeling.
\par \u144\'90There is an alternative first step you can use if you pre
fer.  Each person writes for ten or fifteen minutes--however he or she wants to start.  Then people switch papers for the next piece of writing so that what is written is some kind of response to what the first person wrote.  And so on.  This method adds 
m
ore of the quality of dialogue--thought answering thought.  But by the same token, it can reduce the amount of sheer diversity in the collage, because the writers are more in touch with each other.  In the first, nondialogical method, writers might well b
e in entirely different ball parks--which can be a genuine advantage.  
\par \u144\'90Individually, go back over what you yourself have written and choose the bits and sections you like most.  Some might be a page or more, others very short.  Choose at least twice as much material as you\rquote 
ll need for your contribution to the finished collage.  Clean them up enough to share, but there\rquote s no need to spend too much time on the job.
\par \u144\'90Together in your pair or group, read your individual pieces to each other.  (Or share them through silent reading.)
\par \u144\'90Together, agree on which pieces should be chosen for your collaborative collage.  (Ground rule:  no fair leaving anyone out--or letting anyone dominate the final version.)   
\par \u144\'90Together, give some feedback and suggestions in response to those pieces you have chosen.  But there\rquote s no need for agreement in your responses.  Just let everyone throw in their two cents.  (You\rquote 
ll also have to agree on whether the final revising and polishing of bits should be done by the original authors or by means of trading pieces with each other.)
\par \u144\'90Together, decide on a sequence for all the pieces you\rquote ve chosen.
\par \u144\'90Together, as part of this discussion about sequence, you may well decide you need some new pieces.  Good new ideas might have come up in discussion;  or you might realize that something important is missing.
\par \u144\'90Individually, write any necessary new pieces;  and revise and polish the chosen pieces.   
\par \u144\'90Together, look at what you have produced and decide whether to call it finished or to carry on with m
ore work:  for example, re-ordering of parts;  revising of parts;  writing new parts.  This decision is collaborative, but further work can be individual.
\par }\pard \ql \fi576\li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 Note that some of these tasks require agreement, but many do not.  That is, there is genuine collabor
ation going on here--but only to a limited degree.  This makes it much easier on participants than full collaboration and gives them a good bridge from individual work to group work.  That is, participants }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 don\rquote t}{
\f37\insrsid11210736  have to agree on their ideas, thinking, conclusion, or thesis.  They }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 don\rquote t}{\f37\insrsid11210736 
 have to agree on language, wording, or phrasing.  There are none of those awful tippy-toe discussions or time wasting arguments about how to phrase something.  Nor about the voice or tone.  At every moment, individuals are en
tirely in charge of every piece with respect to thinking, wording, and voice--though of course these decisions are often influenced by comments and feedback from others.  
\par Yet genuine collaboration is also going on--in fact two levels of collaboration:
\par }\pard \ql \fi-144\li864\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin864\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 \u144\'90}{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 Weak collaboration}{\f37\insrsid11210736 :  members read their writing to each other and give and receive individual responses from each other, and thereby }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 influence}{
\f37\insrsid11210736  each others\rquote  thinking and writing;  this collaboration has a substantive effect on the final outcome.  Yet this degree of collaboration is easy and nonstressful because participants don\rquote t have to agree.  
\par \u144\'90}{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 Strong collaboration}{\f37\insrsid11210736 :  participants have to agree on which blips to use;  they have to agree on what order to put them in;  they have to agree on who does the revisi
ng;  they have to agree on whether more revising is needed or whether to call it finished.  Strong collaboration is harder because it requires agreement or consensus.  But the scope of what people have to agree on is pretty limited. 
\par }\pard \ql \fi576\li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 Thus the collaborative
 collage speaks to the first problem of collaboration:  difficulty or unpleasantness.  But can it deal with the other two problems--weak or bland writing and the stifling of minority ideas and voices?  Obviously, it can.  
\par The collaborative collage invites all participants to stay in entirely charge of their own writing, and as a result the final product is richer and more complex than most collaborative writing.  (Even if members decide to revise each others\rquote 
 pieces, single individuals are in charge of thi
nking and language at any given moment.)  The final product contains multiple points of view, multiple voices, multiple styles--and as a result more tension and energy.  Minority ideas and thinking have not been left out.  In a collage, contrasts are a be
nefit, a source of energy that stimulates thinking in readers.  The collaborative collage is a gathering of pieces each written from an \'93I\'94 point of view--for the sake of a \'93we\'94 enterprise.
\par The process I\rquote ve described so far usually results in an }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 open}{\f37\insrsid11210736  collage--a collage with multiple and conflicting points of view.  If the students need to produce a }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 focused}{
\f37\insrsid11210736  collage, they must carry their partial collaboration a few steps further.  They needn\rquote t leave out any of the conflicting material, but they need to
 spend additional time discussing the thinking in their open collage and find a way to agree on a conclusion or at least a common point of view.  And then they need to write, add, arrange, or revise bits--again not taking away any of the contradictory mat
e
rial--in order to make the whole collage end up saying or implying their collaborative conclusion or point of view.  They can even stop short of full agreement if they can agree on where they disagree and articulate that meta-agreement--further spelling o
ut the implications of the various views and explaining what would need to be decided in order to settle their disagreement.  But it\rquote 
s important for students to realize that even though they reach ultimate agreement on a conclusion or point of view, the focused collage still can and really ought to contain wildly divergent and contradictory pieces.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 
\par }{\b\f37\insrsid11210736 Learning to Make Space for Other Voices}{\f37\insrsid11210736 
\par }\pard \ql \fi576\li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\tx10080\tx10800\tx11520\tx12240\tx12960\tx13680\tx14400\wrapdefault\hyphpar0\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11210736 {
\f37\insrsid11210736 Let me briefly suggest three additional methods for helping solo writers begin to get comfortable collaborating with other writers.  These activities can serve as a bridge or introduction even to the mild collaboration I\rquote 
ve already described.
\par (1) The student writes a draft alone, but then shares that draft with one or more others and invites them to write out some of their o
wn thoughts in response:  new thoughts on the topic itself or thoughts about what the writer has said--perhaps even how it was said.  These responses go to the original writer who then gets to incorporate some passages from them into his or her piece.  Th
e writer can put these passages in quotation marks, or in a different type face, or even in a separate column running alongside the writer\rquote 
s own text.  Thus the single writer stays in complete charge of his or her text--but incorporates the voice of others.
\par (2) The student is writing about a topic while also doing lots of reading or interviewing about it.  The student is asked to produce not a conventional, research or documented essay, but a collage that contains extensive and extended quotations from the r
eading or interviews.  Again, the interjected material might be in long block quotations, in separate type-faces, or in a parallel column or two.  The goal here is to help students \'93place\'94
 their own thoughts and voices--in authoritative dialogue with the v
oices of others, especially of published writers.  That is, this procedure can help prevent two common problems in research or documented essays by students:  (a) essays where the writer says almost nothing and merely wholesales the ideas and voices of ot
hers;  (b) essays where the writer brings in nothing but perfunctory \'93quotes\'94 to back up what is essentially his or her own monologue.  
\par (3)  Students work in pairs (or trios) and start by writing a \'93real time\'94 dialogue:  they simply pass a sheet of paper b
ack and forth to each other so each can write a response to the previous turn.  (The process is even easier in an on-line classroom.)  If they want to avoid one writer having to wait while the other one is writing, they can even get two dialogues going on
 
two different topics.  This procedure can seem odd and artificial at first, but students get comfortable pretty quickly if we help them see that they are simply putting on paper what they do naturally and comfortably in spoken conversation.  They usually 
benefit from being encouraged to let the dialogue go where it wants to go, even if it wanders.  It\rquote 
s a voyage of thinking and discovery.  Then the students read over what they have created, and they collaborate on revising it into a satisfying and coherent dialogue.  This doesn\rquote 
t mean the organization or sequence of ideas has to be neat and tidy.  Think about Plato!  Thus the students have to agree about what the main line or direction should be, which parts to keep and discard, and how to arrange or rearran
ge.  But they each get to revise their own contributions.
\par These three processes help students get used to making good texts out of multiple thoughts and voices.
\par 
