\f37\insrsid11210736 I like to use the coll
aborative collage to guide students not only toward better full collaboration, but also toward better solo writing.  That is, the experience of writing and sharing collaborative collages--and seeing the unexpected virtues of them can help students learn t
o
 get into their solo pieces some qualities that are rare and precious in writing:  conflicting ideas, multiple points of view, perplexity, tension, and complexity of structure.  The larger principle of learning that operates here (as articulated by Vygots
ky and Mead) is that we eventually learn to do by ourselves what we first learned to do socially in interaction with others.  We internalize the social process.  
\par That is, much }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 solo}{\f37\insrsid11210736  writing suffers from the same weakness that is found in much collaborative writing.  Many student writers, feeling a pressure always to have a clear \'93thesis,\'94
 end up settling for the lowest-common-denominator point that the various parts of the self can agree on.  They are tempted to stop writing when they feel perplexed or come 
across conflicting feelings and ideas--nervously sweeping complications under the rug.  Students have somehow been led to think that writing should always \'93flow\'94--a favorite word of praise--and thus that the texture should be seamless.  They don
\rquote t realize the pleasure and energy that comes from }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 bumps}{\f37\insrsid11210736 
.  In truth, most good solo writing represents a single writer having some internal dialogue with herself--having more than one point of view and using more than one voice.  Writing needs the drama of thinking and the performance of voices.  
\par All these virtues can be summed up in the catchword that we\rquote ve taken from Bakhtin\rquote s mouth: \'93dialogic.\'94  Fair enough.  But it\rquote s fruitful to encourage some notes of overt }{\i\f37\insrsid11210736 dialogue}{\f37\insrsid11210736 
 into solo writing:  passages where the writer actually breaks out into a different voice and point of view.  It\rquote s not hard to create such passages by using launching pads like these:  \'93
Notice the complications we must consider, however, when we listen to the thoughts of someone who disagrees: \lquote  . . . .\rquote \'94  Or, \'93There are some serious objections, however, to what I have just been saying: \lquote . . . .\rquote \'94
  Or, \'93But wait a minute.  Let\rquote s look at this issue from a contrasting point of view: \lquote  . . . .\rquote \'94  In each case, the writer can carry on for a paragraph or lon
ger speaking in a different voice from a different point of view.  Of course it\rquote s hard to get full rhetorical control over multiple voices and points of view, but even when students don\rquote 
t handle the richness and complexity so well, they almost always gain 
powerful benefits to their thinking.  (Teachers have often found ways to give better grades to papers that fall down--when their downfall stems from the attempt to deal with complex thinking--than to seamless papers that settle for simple, obvious thinkin
g.) 
\par I\rquote 
m fascinated by the literal ability to talk to oneself--to give voice to the multiple views and consciousnesses that inhabit us.  The ability to have thoughtful dialogues with oneself may be one of the most important goals of schooling.  It is surely
 the mark of educated or developed persons to be able to engage in thinking and dialogue when there are no others around who are interested in their topic or interested in talking to them.  One of the biggest difficulties for adolescents in particular, is
 
that they feel so vulnerable to their peers and therefore find it hard to delve very far into issues or feelings or points of view that their peers ignore or scorn as weird.  One of the main things I want to teach my students is that they can pursue their
 ideas even when they feel alone and can\rquote t get others to listen.  
